item.title: Realizing the Future of Health Care
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Increasing health care costs and demand for health care services resulting from an aging and ailing population has made health care unaffordable and has undermined US businesses’ competitiveness in the global economy. Recently enacted health reforms aim to increase access to health care, decrease costs, and improve the quality of care. Innovation in health care technology—ranging from the implementation and use of HIT to the development of new medical devices—will change business models, improve efficiencies, and prove critical to the advancement of low cost, high quality health care. This conference will explore the role of innovation in health care technology in achieving an improved health care system.

item.title: Keynote Speakers
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Rasu Shrestha, MD MBA, Vice President of Medical Information Technology at the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC)

Dr. Shrestha is the VP of Medical Information Technology at UPMC, a $9 billion, 50,000-employee health system serving the needs of more than 4 million people each year. Dr. Shrestha has extensive knowledge of medical informatics and the business of health care. Dr. Shrestha will explore how health care technology can promote patient-centric health care. He will examine future health care technology innovations and discuss the potential for health care technology to transform the current health care system and the delivery of health care.

Don DeLauder, Executive Director of Corporate Innovation, Medrad

Don DeLauder, Executive Director of Corporate Innovation at Medrad, a leading medical device manufacturer focused on computed tomography, magnetic resonance, and cardiovascular applications, will provide a look into the future of health care technology. Mr. DeLauder will discuss strategies for innovation in a dynamic environment increasingly characterized by tight resources and regulation. He will also explore how innovators can identify key customers—from the patient to the physician to health care executives—and deliver value to them.

item.title: Panels
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Disruptions in Health Care via Innovative Medical Devices Technological advancement has been cited as a key driver of health care costs. This panel will discuss how innovation in medical devices can improve efficiency and decrease systemic costs by improving the quality of care. Moderator:
  • Arthur Boni, Ph.D.,  Executive Director, Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship and John R. Thorne Professor of Entrepreneurship, Tepper School of Business
Panelists:
  • Patrick Daly, President and CEO, Cohera Medical Inc.
  • Yali Friedman, Publisher and Editor, Journal of Commercial Biotechnology and Lead Editorial Consultant, Scientific American
  • Craig Markovitz, Founder and CEO, Blue Belt Technologies
  • Christine Robins, CEO, BodyMedia
  • Curtis Stratman, Product Manager, Omnyx
Realizing the Potential of HIT in a Patient-Centered Health Care System This panel will discuss efforts to use HIT to integrate the health care system and facilitate delivery system changes. The panelists will explore the various uses of HIT in health care organizations and provide insight on the facilitators and barriers to implementing HIT and realizing its potential to improve the quality of patient care. Moderator: David Mawhinney, Assistant Teaching Professor of Entrepreneurship; Associate Director, Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship Panelists:
  • Eric Dahlem, Managing Director, Business Transformation Process, sdlc partners
  • Mary Anne Darragh, VP of Health Management Services, Highmark
  • Assaf Halevy, Co-founder and VP of Strategic Accounts and Business Development, dB Motion
  • Jay Srini, Chief Strategist, SCS Ventures
Building Opportunities during Uncertain Economic and Regulatory Transition After providing a brief overview of their company and business model, the panelists will discuss the challenges and opportunities arising from the economic downturn and increased regulation for entrepreneurs. Moderator:
  • Jim Jordan, Chief Investment Officer, Pittsburgh Life Sciences Greenhouse
Panelists:
  • Steve Bollinger, Founder and CEO, Intimate Bridge 2 Conception (invited)
  • Steve Fleck, Founder and Chief Technology Officer, Clear Count
  • Adam Simone, Product Manager, Blue Belt Technologies

item.title: Our Team
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Planning Committee Chair

Jenny Minott Jenny Minott is a second year MBA student at the Tepper School of Business. Jenny graduated from the University of Virginia with a BA in Economics and a minor in Bioethics. Prior to joining Tepper, she conducted best practices research for health care organizations at the Advisory Board Company, and more recently, worked at AcademyHealth evaluating health services research proposals and translating research findings to policymakers. In 2011, Jenny served as President of the BioPharma & Healthcare Club at Tepper working to promote health care careers to students and to increase the visibility of Tepper students to recruiters. Jenny will be joining LEK Consulting in the Fall of 2012 as a Consultant.

Speakers Committee

Megan LeJeune Megan LeJeune is a second-year MBA candidate at the Tepper School of Business of Carnegie Mellon. She has previous experience in biomedical research at UPMC and computational public health research at MIDAS; she is a co-author of multiple publications/pending publications. In 2009, Megan co-founded a nonprofit, Butterfly Medical, dedicated to providing equitable access to health care information and innovation in Health IT, and launched a related summer internship program for students at the University of Pittsburgh shortly after. She was awarded a Forte Fellowship to attend Carnegie Mellon University for graduate school, and had previously earned a Full-Tuition Academic Scholarship to the University of Pittsburgh, where she earned a BS in Molecular Biology.  Her current focus is in Marketing and Strategy, specifically in healthcare and science industries, and she is excited to be joining Becton Dickinson as a Marketing Manager in their Diagnostics division upon graduation. Jenny Sabol Jenny Sabol will be graduating in May with her Master of Science in Health Care Policy and Management from H. John Heinz III College. A Pittsburgh native, she received her bachelor’s degree in rehabilitation science from the University of Pittsburgh in 2009. At Heinz College, Jenny is president of the Health IT Club, works for the Student Activities Committee, and recently initiated the Heinz College Running Club. She has been working as an administrative fellow for UPMC’s Department of Women’s Health since May 2011. Jenny is looking to pursue a career in health care quality, process improvement, and strategy initiatives. Samantha Yeung Samantha Yeung is serving as the first year chair of the Speakers Committee for the inaugural Innovation in Healthcare Technology Conference. Samantha is a first year student at the Heinz College in the Masters of Health Care Policy and Management program. Upon completing her Master’s degree, Samantha is hoping to pursue a career in healthcare management and hospital administration. Prior to to Carnegie Mellon, Samantha received her BS in Biology and Business from Lehigh University.

Marketing Committee Chairs

Catherine Carle As a native Pittsburgher, Catherine strives to reinvent herself through constant immersion in service and work. She completed her undergraduate studies at St. John's University where she majored in Risk Management and Insurance and received a solid foundation in the role of payers and risk financing in the health care sector. At Heinz College she is pursuing her Masters in Health Care Policy and Management with a focus on health informatics, strategy and risk analysis. Catherine hopes that the IHT Conference will serve as a conduit to others, informing them about the rich entrepreneurial opportunity in health care technology and also serving the public. Ultimately, Catherine's goals are to fuse her passion for community, enterprise and health care in an meaningful and impacting manner. Vikrum Ingle Vikrum Ingle comes to Tepper from New Jersey (Turnpike Exit 9) and holds an MS and BS in Industrial Engineering from Rutgers University. He has 4 years experience working in supply chain at medical device companies in the New Jersey area. Vikrum is focusing on Operations, Strategy, and Organizational Behavior and plays volleyball and music in his spare time. This summer he interned with Johnson & Johnson’s Pharmaceutical Research & Development group in the procurement leadership development program. Jeff Mataya Jeff Mataya is currently a second year MBA student at the Tepper School of Business at Carnegie Mellon University. He graduated in 2007 with his B.S. in Computer Science from the University of Michigan and spent three years working as a software engineer at Microsoft. During his time at Tepper, Jeff has been on the founding team of Industry Academics Clinicians Together (IACT), a Pittsburgh organization dedicated to encouraging entrepreneurship and innovation in healthcare technology. Currently concentrating in entrepreneurship, he was the President of the Tepper Entrepreneurship and Venture Capital Club during 2011 and is a James R. Swartz Entrepreneurial Fellow. Jeff is currently focusing on technology entrepreneurship with a particular interest in innovative human-computer interaction and Internet-based technologies within the healthcare industry.

Finance Committee

Adam Yoculan At Tepper, Adam was the 2010-2011 VP of Finance for the BioPharma and Healthcare Club.  Prior to school, Adam worked as Consultant for Sg2 Healthcare Solutions for 3 years developing strategies, recommendations, and performance management tools for health systems. Before that, he worked as a Financial Analyst at MCG Health, a large academic medical center. Adam attended the University of North Carolina where he received a Master of Health Administration and the University of Georgia where he obtained a BBA, majoring in Finance. Following Tepper, Adam will be joining Medtronic in their Leadership Development Program (Finance). In his spare time, Adam likes to enjoy the outdoors with his wife Tatiana and son Alexander.

Logistics Committee Chairs

Jertez Hunter Prior to pursuing his MBA at Tepper, Jertez served in the US Army for 7 years as an Armor Captain. His leadership was instrumental in organizing a Medical Civic Action Program (MEDCAP) in Basra, Iraq to provide basic medical treatment to citizens that were most in need. Jertez will spend this summer working for Eli Lilly as a marketing intern.   Jillian Walker Jillian Walker is pursuing a Master's of Science degree in Biotechnology and Management which is an interdisciplinary collaboration between various departments and colleges at Carnegie Mellon University. Jillian has an undergraduate degree in Chemical Engineering from Villanova University. She currently has an internship at a start-up orthopedic medical device company called Blue Belt Technologies. Her interests are in product development and regulatory affairs of medical devices.

President, BioPharma & Healthcare Club

Heather Martin Before coming to Tepper, Heather Rae Martin spent three years working as an Analytical Chemist and Research Scientist in the Greater St. Louis, MO area for global pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies. She is pursuing concentrations in both Marketing and Strategy within the MBA program.  She will spend this summer at Amgen as a Sales and Marketing Grad Intern.

item.title: Directions
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Getting to Campus

The conference will be held on Carnegie Mellon University's campus in Pittsburgh and will be split between the University Center (denoted by the green arrow on the map below), Hamburg Hall, and Posner Hall. The University Center is located at 5000 Forbes Ave, Pittsburgh, PA 15232. View Larger Map

Parking

Parking is available for a fee in a garage next to the University Center at the intersection of Forbes and Beeler Streets.

Getting Around Campus

Hamburg Hall, home to the J. Heinz College, is located on Forbes Avenue between South Neville Street and Morewood Avenue. Posner Hall, home to the Tepper School of Business, is located at the corner of  Tech Street and Frew Street. Please see the Carnegie Mellon University campus map for details about how to get around campus. Hamburg Hall is building 11, Posner Hall is building 19, and the University Center is building 29. The recommended parking garage is labeled P7.

Keynote Speaker Biographies Rasu Shrestha, MD, MBA, Vice President of Medical Information Technology, University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC) Dr. Shrestha has extensive knowledge of medical informatics and the business of health care. Dr. Shrestha is also the Medical Director of Interoperability & Imaging Informatics and Division Chief of Radiology Informatics. UPMC spans over 20 hospitals operating over 4,200 beds, 30 imaging centers, and conducts 2 million radiology examinations per year. UPMC is a $9 billion, 50,000-employee organization that serves the needs of more than 4 million people each year. Dr. Shrestha was previously the Medical Director of Digital Imaging Informatics at UPMC where he had spearheaded multiple initiatives around imaging interoperability, and continues to do so across the enterprise. Prior to joining UPMC, Dr. Shrestha was Informatics Director at the University of Southern California, Department of Radiology. Dr. Shrestha was also Professor of Radiology Research at the Keck School of Medicine and has a unique blend of clinical as well as research skills in Medical Informatics. Dr. Shrestha has proven expertise in driving efficiency and productivity, managing multi-vendor dealings and leading process improvement and major enterprise informatics implementations around various Clinical Information Systems. These include PACS (Picture Archiving and Communication Systems), RIS (Radiology Informatics System), EMR (Electronic Medical Records) and Voice Recognition as well as related NLP (Natural Language Processing) technologies. His core focus is on modernizing and optimizing patient care primarily in the health care informatics arena, maximizing revenue, excellence in teaching, research collaboration and enterprise wide efficiency optimizations. Dr. Shrestha’s focus has also been on enabling a patient-centric approach to care, where care can progress beyond the silos of information systems, as healthcare moves from mere repositories of information to knowledge and actionable data. He is driven by the pursuit of intelligent healthcare, enabling meaningful data connectivity and collaborative intelligence. Don DeLauder, Executive Director of Corporate Innovation, Medrad Don is the Executive Director of Corporate Innovation for Bayer Radiology and Interventional, which includes the former MEDRAD, a Pittsburgh-based manufacturer of innovative medical equipment and disposable products used in diagnostic imaging and vascular intervention procedures. Don is currently responsible for managing technology development to expand the company’s product opportunities and intellectual property portfolio. Previously, Don managed the Product Development Engineering organization at MEDRAD, encompassing all of the engineering disciplines involved in new product development. Don holds an MBA from the University of Michigan, as well as Master’s and Bachelor’s degrees in Electrical Engineering from West Virginia University. While at West Virginia University, he was also a Swiger Doctoral Fellow, during which he completed his PhD coursework. He is a founding member of the Pittsburgh chapter of the Product Development Management Association (PDMA). Medical Device Panel Biographies Arthur A. Boni, Ph.D., John R. Thorne Chair of Entrepreneurship and Director of the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship, Tepper School of Business Arthur A. Boni, Ph.D., has held the John R. Thorne Chair of Entrepreneurship at the Tepper School of Business at Carnegie Mellon University since 2003, and is the Director of the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship. He teaches undergraduates, MBAs, and executives in emerging companies.  His teaching and research interests include: entrepreneurship and new venture creation, commercialization of technology and biotechnology, venture capital investing, innovation and entrepreneurship in organizations, leadership and broad-based ownership in entrepreneurial companies, and biopharmaceutical and alternative energy industries. Dr. Boni’s educational background includes a B.S. from Carnegie Mellon University (Mechanical Engineering), an M.S. from the University of Southern California (Mechanical Engineering), and a Ph.D. from the University of California, San Diego (Engineering Science/Engineering Physics).  He served as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Engineering and Applied Science at Yale University and has over 80 open literature publications. Patrick Daly, President & Chief Executive Officer, Cohera Medical Mr. Daly has over 20 years of experience in medical device sales, marketing, international marketing and leadership positions throughout the Johnson & Johnson organization including Ethicon Endo-Surgery, Ethicon Products, J&J Medical Australia/New Zealand, J&J Medical Asia Pacific and Cohera Medical, Inc.® Within Johnson & Johnson, he held positions of increasing responsibility in marketing, international marketing and sales. He successfully launched a surgical technology business in Australia and created and implemented the first-ever regulatory review of safety and efficacy of that new technology by the Australian Government. He continued his Johnson & Johnson entrepreneurial-like career track as a marketing leader in J&J Medical Asia Pacific by creating and implementing training and development programs in China, India, Korea, Singapore, and the Philippines. Mr. Daly started Cohera Medical in January 2006 and led three successful funding rounds of over $40.5M in capital from private investors to facilitate Cohera Medical’s lead product TissuGlu® Surgical Adhesive through the FDA approval process for medical devices. Prior to joining Cohera Medical and Johnson & Johnson, Mr. Daly spent over four years on active duty in the U.S. Army as a field artillery officer serving around the world. A native of New York, he is a graduate of the U.S. Military Academy at West Point where he received a B.S. in Engineering with a concentration in Latin American Studies. He played varsity lacrosse during his four years at West Point and was an All-American. Mr. Daly serves on the Board of the Pittsburgh Technology Council and Girls Hope, a nonprofit that provides a well-balanced, nurturing home and quality education through college for academically capable girls. He is also a member of the Young Presidents Organization. Yali Friedman Bio forthcoming Craig Markovitz, Principal of MDM Ventures, Founder of Blue Belt Technologies and Spotlight Medical, Inc. Craig Markovitz is an experienced entrepreneur with a history of successful technology commercialization. He is currently Principal of MDL Ventures, LLC, providing strategic coaching, advice, expertise and guidance to entrepreneurs, universities, health care institutions and economic development organizations. He is a founder, and currently a board member and adviser of Blue Belt Technologies as well as a founder of Spotlight Medical, Inc. Prior to founding Blue Belt and Spotlight, Markovitz worked with The Redleaf Group, Inc., a $285 million early stage venture capital fund, as the Chief Operating Officer of PenNetWorks, LLC at the University of Pennsylvania. Before joining Redleaf, Markovitz was an independent consultant providing services to university technology transfer offices and early stage businesses. Prior to this, Markovitz managed a $50 million portfolio as a corporate lender for PNC Bank and performed customer service and marketing activities for Nortel Networks in Chicago, IL. Markovitz graduated with distinction from the MBA program at the Charles H. Kellstadt Graduate School of Business at DePaul University in Chicago with a degree in Entrepreneurship, and graduated cum laude from Washington and Jefferson College in Washington, PA with a B.A. in Management. He has also taken continuing education courses at Carnegie Mellon University. He is an active speaker, mentor and guest lecturer at various universities and events discussing topics such as: technology transfer, private equity investment, business start up and financing strategies, and other entrepreneurial topics. He lives in Pittsburgh, PA with his wife and three children. Christine Robins, Chief Executive Officer, BodyMedia Christine Robins is the current Chief Executive Officer of BodyMedia, Inc.; a pioneer in developing and marketing wearable body monitors. BodyMedia’s devices are unparalleled in the marketplace for validated accuracy and proven outcomes to help people lead healthier lives. Prior to joining BodyMedia, Christine was the CEO of Philips Oral Healthcare where she led the global Sonicare® brand to significant sales and share growth.  This experience led Chris to develop a deep understanding for the integration of professional and consumer business models. Christine also has extensive experience in a wide range of marketing and finance capacities gained during her 17 years at S.C. Johnson, where she ran notable brands such as Raid® insecticides, Glade® air fresheners, Aveeno® skin care products and Ziploc® bags. With this background rooted in global multi-national companies and an entrepreneurial zeal essential to lead a high technology upstart, Chris is passionate about developing strategy, building teams and driving innovation. A noted speaker, Christine has delivered presentations at universities such as Harvard & Duke as well as keynotes at industry shows such as CES and CTIA.  She holds a degree in Marketing and Finance from the University of Wisconsin-Madison and an MBA from Marquette University. Curtis Stratman bio forthcoming Health Information Technology Panel Eric Dahlem, Business Transformation Practice Managing Director, sdlc partners Eric Dahlem is sdlc’s Business Transformation Practice Managing Director.  He has over fourteen (14) years of experience developing and implementing comprehensive business process reengineering programs.  He has led and delivered reengineering projects in medical management, consumer driven healthcare, health plan operations, and product management / marketing.  Eric has delivered a broad range of consulting expertise in areas that include business process management, e-business, and information security / risk management.  His other clients have included large health care providers and plans, pharmaceuticals, industrial manufacturers and the federal government.  Mr. Dahlem has a BS in Information & Decision Systems and a MS in Information Technology Management from Carnegie Mellon University and is a Certified Information Systems Security Professional (CISSP). Mary Ann Darragh, VP of Health Management Services, Highmark Bio forthcoming

Assaf Halevy, Co-founder and VP of Strategic Accounts and Business Development, dB Motion

Assaf Halevy, Co-Founder and Vice President of Business Development and Strategic Accounts, is one of the inventors of the dbMotion Solution and responsible for a patent application in this field. He has been involved in many aspects of the company's growth including management of the development team responsible for the healthcare products line and international operations manager.

While dbMotion was under the corporate umbrella of Ness Technologies (as Ness ISI), Mr. Halevy was involved in evaluating strategic partnerships, due diligence and business development in Ness Technologies' international markets. Mr. Halevy has focused on medical informatics, both in the local and international arena, and directed dbMotion to become an innovative and unique solution in the healthcare market. Mr. Halevy holds a BA, with honors, in Computer Science from The Academic College of Tel Aviv-Jaffa and Tel Aviv University.

David Mawhinney, Assistant Teaching Professor of Entrepreneurship; Associate Director, Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship; Managing Director, Open Field Entrepreneurs Fund; Director i6 Agile Innovation System, a collaboration between InnovationWorks and Carnegie Mellon University Prior to joining Carnegie Mellon, Dave was co-founder, Chairman and CEO of  mSpoke, an internet content and advertising recommendation engine, was acquired in 2010 by LinkedIn, the world’s leading professional social networking site.  In 2006, Morgan Stanley’s MSCI/Barra business unit acquired mSpoke’s first business line, a quantitative investment recommendation engine. Prior to mSpoke, Dave was a General Partner of PNC Technology Investors. Earlier in his career, he co-founded three successful startup ventures before that, including Premier Health Exchange (acquired by Medibuy), Hawk Medical (acquired by McKesson), and Industry.Net (merged with AT&T Business Network to form Nets, Inc.). Dave is also an active Board Member at MedSage Technologies (now NewCare Solutions LLC), EZ-FLO Injection Systems, CloudFab LLC, SnapRetail, and the Indiana University of Pennsylvania Alumni Association (ex-officio, Past President.).  He is an Advisory Board Member to InnovationWork’s AlphaLab, Pittsburgh Equity Partners, and Carnegie Mellon University’s Project Olympus.  Dave also served as Executive-in-Residence at the Pittsburgh Life Sciences Greenhouse working with healthcare information technology start-ups. Dave lives with his wife Kristan and three sons in Fox Chapel, PA. Mr. Mawhinney holds an MBA with Distinction from Carnegie Mellon University and a B. S. in Physics, Summa Cum Laude, from Indiana University of Pennsylvania. Jay Srini, Chief Strategist, SCS Ventures Jay Srini is currently serving as the Chief Strategist at SCS Ventures where she is working with startup companies internationally to help them with their business development, technology strategy and expansion. The business models for the client companies range from e-health to personal health management, and telemedicine. Jay’s prior experience includes her role as Chief Innovation Officer for UPMC Insurance Services Division as well as her role as Vice President of Emerging Technologies for UPMC. Her responsibilities as VP of Emerging Technologies included providing strategic direction and input regarding emerging technologies and solutions to UPMC and their Insurances subsidiary. Jay was Managing Director for e-Health Initiatives at Internet Venture Works where she led technology and industry assessments of opportunities presented by strategic partners, investors and external sources and served in interim executive management roles for its' portfolio companies before joining UPMC as VP of Emerging Technologies. Jay has a Master's Degree in Computer Science from New York University and a Master's Degree in Business Administration from Bucknell University and her executive education from the Kellogg School of Management at Northwestern University. She also serves on the advisory board of several entrepreneurial companies, nonprofit health care organizations and serves as one of the commissioners at CCHIT (Certification Commission of HealthCare Information Technology) in addition to her role as adjunct faculty at the University of Pittsburgh. Entrepreneurship Panel Steve Fleck, Co-Founder and Chief Technology Officer, Clear Count Bio forthcoming Jim Jordan, Chief Investment Officer, Pittsburgh Life Sciences Greenhouse Bio forthcoming Adam Simone, Product Manager, Blue Belt Technologies Adam graduated from Carnegie Mellon with a masters degree in Biotechnology and Management, with focused study on the medical device industry.  Since 2009, he has been a part of Pittsburgh start-up Blue Belt Technologies where he is working towards commercialization of a flagship surgical robotics system.  In January 2011, Blue Belt was acquired by New York-based private equity firm Healthpoint Capital.  Prior to his current role as global Product Manager, Adam developed and implemented an ISO certified quality management system. He holds a BS in Mechanical Engineering from Northeastern University in Boston, where he began his professional career in consumer product development with companies like P&G and Hasbro. Adam lives in Pittsburgh’s strip district with his two plants.    

Dave Mawhinney, Carnegie Mellon University:  Managing Director, Open Field Entrepreneurs Fund, Associate Director Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship, and Director, i6 Agile Innovation System, a collaboration between InnovationWorks and Carnegie Mellon University

Prior to joining Carnegie Mellon, Dave was co-founder, Chairman and CEO of  mSpoke, an internet content and advertising recommendation engine, was acquired in 2010 by LinkedIn, the world’s leading professional social networking site.  In 2006, Morgan Stanley’s MSCI/Barra business unit acquired mSpoke’s first business line, a quantitative investment recommendation engine.

Prior to mSpoke, Dave was a General Partner of PNC Technology Investors. Earlier in his career, he co-founded three successful startup ventures before that, including Premier Health Exchange (acquired by Medibuy), Hawk Medical (acquired by McKesson), and Industry.Net (merged with AT&T Business Network to form Nets, Inc.).

Dave is also an active Board Member at MedSage Technologies (now NewCare Solutions LLC), EZ-FLO Injection Systems, CloudFab LLC, SnapRetail, and the Indiana University of Pennsylvania Alumni Association (ex-officio, Past President.).  He is an Advisory Board Member to InnovationWork’s AlphaLab, Pittsburgh Equity Partners, and Carnegie Mellon University’s Project Olympus.  Dave also served as Executive-in-Residence at the Pittsburgh Life Sciences Greenhouse working with healthcare information technology start-ups.

Dave lives with his wife Kristan and three sons in Fox Chapel, PA.

Mr. Mawhinney holds an MBA with Distinction from Carnegie Mellon University and a B. S. in Physics, Summa Cum Laude, from Indiana University of Pennsylvania.
